satellites soon to come.

01:04:43.150 --> 01:04:46.060
So Eisenhower wasn't
wrong, and Kennedy

01:04:46.060 --> 01:04:50.100
was briefed by Allen Dulles
after he got nominated,

01:04:50.100 --> 01:04:51.970
and Lyndon too.

01:04:51.970 --> 01:04:55.090
They were briefed after the
Los Angeles convention in 1960

01:04:55.090 --> 01:04:57.370
by Allen Dulles and the CIA.

01:04:57.370 --> 01:04:59.740
And they showed them all
the papers from these spy

01:04:59.740 --> 01:05:05.260
satellites that we were actually
ahead of Russia in satellite

01:05:05.260 --> 01:05:07.270
technology and missiles.

01:05:07.270 --> 01:05:10.030
And Kennedy, the big
question is, did Kennedy

01:05:10.030 --> 01:05:11.680
process that,
because he shouldn't

01:05:11.680 --> 01:05:14.240
do that on the campaign trail.

01:05:14.240 --> 01:05:17.140
And if you go to the
Kennedy-Nixon debates, which

01:05:17.140 --> 01:05:19.240
I had to go back to,
they're fascinating,

01:05:19.240 --> 01:05:23.020
but I think Kennedy, some
of his best punches at Nixon

01:05:23.020 --> 01:05:27.850
was when he was saying that
you spoke to Khrushchev,

01:05:27.850 --> 01:05:30.880
the famous kitchen
debate, when Nixon debated

01:05:30.880 --> 01:05:36.730
Khrushchev about who has better
appliances, kitchen appliances.

01:05:36.730 --> 01:05:39.570
And Kennedy said, you
had told Khrushchev

01:05:39.570 --> 01:05:43.480
that we're beating them in
appliances, kitchen appliances.

01:05:43.480 --> 01:05:46.630
Well, I'll take my TV
in black and white.

01:05:46.630 --> 01:05:49.960
I want to be number
one in rocket thrust.

01:05:49.960 --> 01:05:53.320
And then he insinuated
that, in one of the debates

01:05:53.320 --> 01:05:57.160
said if Nixon's elected, I
see a Soviet flag planted

01:05:57.160 --> 01:06:00.970
on the moon, not an American
one, in one of the debates.

01:06:00.970 --> 01:06:03.230
But what Kennedy knew
and found out quickly

01:06:03.230 --> 01:06:05.230
when he was president,
we were doing pretty well

01:06:05.230 --> 01:06:05.980
on the tech front.

01:06:05.980 --> 01:06:09.460
NASA created in '58,
civilian, but our technology

01:06:09.460 --> 01:06:11.590
and satellites
were coming along,

01:06:11.590 --> 01:06:14.020
and he recognized
that really Eisenhower

01:06:14.020 --> 01:06:18.100
did a pretty good job of
keeping America defense-ready

01:06:18.100 --> 01:06:23.470
and doing R&amp;D on ICBMs and
intermediate range missiles.

01:06:23.470 --> 01:06:25.330
And the Jupiter
missiles you guys

01:06:25.330 --> 01:06:27.400
will hear about if you're
a Cuban Missile Crisis

01:06:27.400 --> 01:06:31.600
person, that are on Turkey,
that we put there on Turkey,

01:06:31.600 --> 01:06:35.400
those were the junk missiles
of Wernher Von Braun.

01:06:35.400 --> 01:06:37.660
He built them for
defense purposes.

01:06:37.660 --> 01:06:40.090
They weren't that effective,
and we put them on the border

01:06:40.090 --> 01:06:42.790
there with Turkey.

01:06:42.790 --> 01:06:44.590
And during the Cuban
Missile Crisis,

01:06:44.590 --> 01:06:46.630
where the United
States of course

01:06:46.630 --> 01:06:49.150
does the deal to eventually
get rid of those,

01:06:49.150 --> 01:06:51.950
the Soviets don't build
the launching things there.

01:06:51.950 --> 01:06:53.920
So keep in mind
with the moon, it's

01:06:53.920 --> 01:06:58.670
a lot about missile
technology, spy satellites.

01:06:58.670 --> 01:07:01.810
And out of all of this
technology, GPS of today,

01:07:01.810 --> 01:07:06.340
global positioning systems is
pioneered by NASA/ I don't like

01:07:06.340 --> 01:07:08.950
to say "invent things,"
because I found out in my book,

01:07:08.950 --> 01:07:12.400
like everybody says that
Velcro was created by NASA.

01:07:12.400 --> 01:07:16.880
I found out it
isn't, nor is Tang.

01:07:16.880 --> 01:07:20.320
Velcro was a Swiss
gentleman in World War II

01:07:20.320 --> 01:07:23.560
who would do alpine hikes with
his border collie sheep dog

01:07:23.560 --> 01:07:24.280
or whatever.

01:07:24.280 --> 01:07:26.260
And it would get
burrs in its fur,

01:07:26.260 --> 01:07:29.980
and he created Velcro to get
the burrs off the dog's fur.

01:07:29.980 --> 01:07:33.610
But what is true is NASA
uses it and applies it

01:07:33.610 --> 01:07:37.630
in the space program, and
now Velcro, it's ubiquitous.

01:07:37.630 --> 01:07:40.130
Much of the tech--

01:07:40.130 --> 01:07:42.470
radar being created
is important, guys.

01:07:42.470 --> 01:07:46.400
MIT computer
technology is gigantic.

01:07:46.400 --> 01:07:48.990
The computer system
of going the moon

01:07:48.990 --> 01:07:52.180
is done right here in
Cambridge, Massachusetts.

01:07:52.180 --> 01:07:56.640
A woman, Miss Hamilton,
was the pioneer in it,

01:07:56.640 --> 01:08:00.260
in Stark Draper's laboratory
and the work that they

01:08:00.260 --> 01:08:02.210
did there at MIT is phenomenal.

01:08:02.210 --> 01:08:06.320
And the Draper family, a
great American family, and I

01:08:06.320 --> 01:08:09.050
appreciate all that they've
done for the Kennedy Library

01:08:09.050 --> 01:08:13.250
but also for America in general
by funding and pioneering

01:08:13.250 --> 01:08:17.510
and hiring the right people
to do the right amount of R&amp;D

01:08:17.510 --> 01:08:19.760
in order to be in space.

01:08:19.760 --> 01:08:21.920
So thank you to
the Draper family.

01:08:21.920 --> 01:08:23.420
FREDERIK LOGEVALL:
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY:

01:08:23.420 --> 01:08:26.013
Let's go to this side, please.

01:08:26.013 --> 01:08:28.468
[COUGHING]

01:08:30.439 --> 01:08:32.680
AUDIENCE: Something you
may not be aware of--

01:08:32.680 --> 01:08:35.450
I guess I'm going to have to
go on with this, pardon me--

01:08:35.450 --> 01:08:39.500
is that the US Department
of Transportation's National

01:08:39.500 --> 01:08:41.479
Research Center is in Cambridge.

01:08:41.479 --> 01:08:45.460
But that was originally intended
to be a NASA research center,

01:08:45.460 --> 01:08:50.479
and when John Volpe,
governor of Massachusetts,

01:08:50.479 --> 01:08:54.770
became Secretary, the first
Secretary of Transportation,

01:08:54.770 --> 01:09:00.770
he swung the bucks, the
transportation bucks to here.

01:09:00.770 --> 01:09:05.060
I was a fledgling
engineer, newly

01:09:05.060 --> 01:09:08.479
arrived in Washington, DC, and
watched with rapt attention

01:09:08.479 --> 01:09:10.880
when the moon landing happened.

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:13.130
And I was thrilled, and
I've followed the space race

01:09:13.130 --> 01:09:16.109
ever since, and I've read
a lot of books about it,

01:09:16.109 --> 01:09:18.020
and I'm really looking
forward to this.

01:09:18.020 --> 01:09:21.380
My question is, when
John F Kennedy declared

01:09:21.380 --> 01:09:22.939
that we were going
to go to the moon,

01:09:22.939 --> 01:09:26.600
had he consulted with
scientists and engineers,

01:09:26.600 --> 01:09:31.069
so he had some feeling that
this was a doable thing?

01:09:31.069 --> 01:09:35.870
Or did he actually, as you
implied, spring this on NASA?

01:09:35.870 --> 01:09:37.939
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY:
No, great questions.

01:09:37.939 --> 01:09:40.189
And I did not know that
about transportation.

01:09:40.189 --> 01:09:41.240
Very interesting to me.

01:09:41.240 --> 01:09:43.970
Thank you for educating
me about that.

01:09:43.970 --> 01:09:46.550
But in my book, I write a
lot and they have them here

01:09:46.550 --> 01:09:49.830
at the Kennedy Library, the
memos of '61 going back,

01:09:49.830 --> 01:09:53.330
where Kennedy tells Lyndon
Johnson "gimme answers."

01:09:53.330 --> 01:09:54.530
"What can we do?

01:09:54.530 --> 01:09:55.640
I want the leapfrog.

01:09:55.640 --> 01:09:56.930
Give me big answers."

01:09:56.930 --> 01:09:58.070
And it gets spread.

01:09:58.070 --> 01:10:01.230
All of our experts
start weighing in on it.

01:10:01.230 --> 01:10:03.590
Later Kennedy comes
in, he decided

01:10:03.590 --> 01:10:06.660
to go with the very
radical going to the moon,

01:10:06.660 --> 01:10:08.660
but Lyndon Johnson
thought it was doable.

01:10:08.660 --> 01:10:10.550
Wernher Von Braun
thought it was doable.

01:10:10.550 --> 01:10:12.120
Webb thought it was doable.

01:10:12.120 --> 01:10:13.520
They're just the big names.

01:10:13.520 --> 01:10:15.890
But under them, they
talked to the engineers,

01:10:15.890 --> 01:10:18.410
and they didn't
know how, but what

01:10:18.410 --> 01:10:20.450
they knew from intelligence
is it would be,

01:10:20.450 --> 01:10:23.930
again, this fair start, that
we didn't think the Soviets--

01:10:23.930 --> 01:10:26.750
And one of the important
things, that the Soviets

01:10:26.750 --> 01:10:29.720
were trying to go to the moon,
some people it's like a myth

01:10:29.720 --> 01:10:32.240
that we weren't
really in a race.

01:10:32.240 --> 01:10:35.070
When the Soviet Union
dissolved in 1991,

01:10:35.070 --> 01:10:38.480
and when East Germany,
German unification

01:10:38.480 --> 01:10:41.030
occurred and we got
archives over there,

01:10:41.030 --> 01:10:42.662
we now have the Soviet archives.

01:10:42.662 --> 01:10:44.120
They were trying
to get to the moon

01:10:44.120 --> 01:10:48.510
right up until they had
failures in '67, '68.

01:10:48.510 --> 01:10:49.850
They were right on it.

01:10:49.850 --> 01:10:53.960
They were about ready to put
tortoises on the moon right

01:10:53.960 --> 01:10:57.080
before all this happened,
but they had a major disaster

01:10:57.080 --> 01:11:00.410
of their own in Kazakhstan.

01:11:00.410 --> 01:11:03.310
And that's where a lot
of the Soviet money--

01:11:03.310 --> 01:11:06.560
I'm talking about the Southern
states getting money for space.

01:11:06.560 --> 01:11:09.470
In Russia, Kazakhstan
got the money,

01:11:09.470 --> 01:11:11.690
because that was a
way for Khrushchev

01:11:11.690 --> 01:11:16.100
to help a region that
needed some economic lift.

01:11:16.100 --> 01:11:19.100
And so it's really interesting.

01:11:19.100 --> 01:11:21.350
Also your point that you
mentioned you're an engineer,

01:11:21.350 --> 01:11:23.750
and it just dawned on
me, I wanted to tell you.

01:11:23.750 --> 01:11:28.190
So in my oral history of Neil
Armstrong, he is Mr. Engineer--

01:11:28.190 --> 01:11:30.800
Purdue, engineer, engineer.

01:11:30.800 --> 01:11:34.070
There's no better example of
an engineer than Armstrong.

01:11:34.070 --> 01:11:36.830
And he spent his whole
life, including to me,

01:11:36.830 --> 01:11:40.130
but to everybody that
we don't honor engineers

01:11:40.130 --> 01:11:41.750
enough in American history.

01:11:41.750 --> 01:11:45.131
So I'm honoring the
engineers tonight.

01:11:45.131 --> 01:11:47.516
[APPLAUSE]

01:11:51.180 --> 01:11:55.500
But I'm a humanities guy,
and I'm not an engineer.

01:11:55.500 --> 01:12:00.000
And I tried to get him off
of that engineer mind of his,

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:03.930
and I said, "Mr. Armstrong, did
you go out and just stand up

01:12:03.930 --> 01:12:08.760
there and look up at the moon
and see it glowing up there

01:12:08.760 --> 01:12:12.630
and say, 'My goodness, I'm
going to be standing there,

01:12:12.630 --> 01:12:14.610
looking at earth'"?

01:12:14.610 --> 01:12:15.110
"No."

01:12:20.270 --> 01:12:21.740
He wasn't messing with me.

01:12:21.740 --> 01:12:25.140
His mind just didn't
work that way.

01:12:25.140 --> 01:12:26.960
An interesting, though,
little side thing,

01:12:26.960 --> 01:12:30.380
do you guys remember the writers
Tom Wolfe, The Right Stuff

01:12:30.380 --> 01:12:34.610
book, and Norman Mailer wrote
a book on going to the moon?

01:12:34.610 --> 01:12:37.760
Armstrong thought Mailer's
was pretty interesting,

01:12:37.760 --> 01:12:40.940
only because he was talking in
Mailer's book about the dangers

01:12:40.940 --> 01:12:42.380
of technology.

01:12:42.380 --> 01:12:45.470
And mailer put himself as
the main figure in the book,

01:12:45.470 --> 01:12:47.330
but I did get him to
say that about any

01:12:47.330 --> 01:12:48.950
of those kind of
space things, he

01:12:48.950 --> 01:12:52.160
thought Mailer raising some of
the problems with technology

01:12:52.160 --> 01:12:54.510
was quite interesting.

01:12:54.510 --> 01:12:57.560
And also, he was
very self-effacing.

01:12:57.560 --> 01:13:02.150
James Michener had a pseudonym
for a pilot in the Korean War.

01:13:02.150 --> 01:13:05.060
He was with Armstrong's ship
out in the Korean War, James

01:13:05.060 --> 01:13:07.410
Michener, the great
writer, and noticed it.

01:13:07.410 --> 01:13:09.320
I don't have time
tonight, but Armstrong

01:13:09.320 --> 01:13:11.330
was an exceptional pilot.

01:13:13.850 --> 01:13:17.510
You can't read about a better
pilot than Neil Armstrong, what

01:13:17.510 --> 01:13:18.680
he could do with planes.

01:13:18.680 --> 01:13:22.790
And the reason he went to Purdue
and Gus Grissom went to Purdue.

01:13:22.790 --> 01:13:24.830
And young people here,
this is pretty cool,

01:13:24.830 --> 01:13:27.770
if you go to college,
Purdue was the first one

01:13:27.770 --> 01:13:29.870
to give you-- if
you went there, you

01:13:29.870 --> 01:13:33.990
could take a class in
aviation history about planes

01:13:33.990 --> 01:13:37.880
and earn your pilot's
license in the classes.

01:13:37.880 --> 01:13:41.390
So a lot of these guys that
loved airplanes wanted to go

01:13:41.390 --> 01:13:43.557
to Purdue, because they
could get their pilot's--

01:13:43.557 --> 01:13:45.140
I mean, I'm talking
about 18-year-olds

01:13:45.140 --> 01:13:46.640
that want a pilot's license.

01:13:46.640 --> 01:13:48.750
It would be part of
their degree program

01:13:48.750 --> 01:13:52.450
that when they leave
college they could fly.

01:13:52.450 --> 01:13:56.120
And so Purdue produced so
many of our astronauts,

01:13:56.120 --> 01:14:00.355
because they have an airport
on the campus for students.

01:14:00.355 --> 01:14:01.730
FREDERIK LOGEVALL:
Isn't it nice?

01:14:01.730 --> 01:14:07.120
Isn't it nice, ladies and
gentlemen, to have just a,

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:09.810
shall I say, an
extolling of expertise?

01:14:09.810 --> 01:14:13.258
I mean, it comes
through in this book.

01:14:13.258 --> 01:14:15.300
And in this day and age,
I think at least for me,

01:14:15.300 --> 01:14:16.080
it just resonates.

01:14:16.080 --> 01:14:19.820
It's not to say that
experts don't get it wrong.

01:14:19.820 --> 01:14:22.430
As Doug indicated, I've spent
a lot of my career researching

01:14:22.430 --> 01:14:24.620
the Vietnam War, and
there are lots of experts

01:14:24.620 --> 01:14:25.920
who got that story wrong.

01:14:25.920 --> 01:14:29.320
But nevertheless, John F
Kennedy had a commitment

01:14:29.320 --> 01:14:32.660
to fact-based discourse
right to the end,

01:14:32.660 --> 01:14:35.570
and I think it
matters a great deal.

01:14:35.570 --> 01:14:37.040
Sir?

01:14:37.040 --> 01:14:39.143
AUDIENCE: So the Third
Reich ran out of gas, huh?

01:14:39.143 --> 01:14:41.060
That's a pretty provocative
way of putting it.

01:14:41.060 --> 01:14:45.110
But in '67, there was an
International Outer Space

01:14:45.110 --> 01:14:46.910
Treaty convened.

01:14:46.910 --> 01:14:49.980
As of this year, 108 countries
have signed on to it,

01:14:49.980 --> 01:14:51.230
including the United States.

01:14:51.230 --> 01:14:53.780
It prevents weapons
of mass destruction

01:14:53.780 --> 01:14:56.690
from being deployed in space,
but not conventional weapons.

01:14:56.690 --> 01:14:59.450
And after that, in
'79, there was actually

01:14:59.450 --> 01:15:02.750
a moon treaty that was
proposed and written,

01:15:02.750 --> 01:15:04.730
and only 10 countries
signed on to that.

01:15:04.730 --> 01:15:06.320
The United States
is not one of them,

01:15:06.320 --> 01:15:09.260
but that would prevent any type
of weapons and military bases

01:15:09.260 --> 01:15:11.870
on any celestial bodies,
including the moon.

01:15:11.870 --> 01:15:14.120
Now, the president
has recently proposed

01:15:14.120 --> 01:15:16.760
and has gotten funding
for a new space

01:15:16.760 --> 01:15:19.610
force, not an international
one but a United States one,

01:15:19.610 --> 01:15:22.250
which brings these
questions back to mind.

01:15:22.250 --> 01:15:26.150
Do we need a treaty that would
prohibit the militarization

01:15:26.150 --> 01:15:29.690
of space, and including
conventional weapons

01:15:29.690 --> 01:15:31.820
as well as any celestial bodies?

01:15:31.820 --> 01:15:35.450
Now, you can opine based on your
historical knowledge on what

01:15:35.450 --> 01:15:38.700
JFK might have done and
also look into the future,

01:15:38.700 --> 01:15:42.200
but we have to be considering
that these space programs do

01:15:42.200 --> 01:15:47.720
contain and are implicitly
designed for militarization

01:15:47.720 --> 01:15:49.490
at some point too, don't we?

01:15:49.490 --> 01:15:51.130
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY: Yes, we do.

01:15:51.130 --> 01:15:53.660
If you don't know,
there are two things

01:15:53.660 --> 01:15:56.150
that the Trump administration
is promoting right now

01:15:56.150 --> 01:15:59.030
and many more, obviously,
but two just quickly.

01:15:59.030 --> 01:16:02.830
Space Force, which I don't
think is a very good idea.

01:16:02.830 --> 01:16:04.550
It leads to what
you're suggesting,

01:16:04.550 --> 01:16:06.920
militarization of space.

01:16:06.920 --> 01:16:10.100
And it's not very practical,
because the Navy doesn't want

01:16:10.100 --> 01:16:13.220
a new branch, Army
doesn't, Air Force doesn't.

01:16:13.220 --> 01:16:16.880
So I don't think Space Force
is going to get much momentum.

01:16:16.880 --> 01:16:19.250
Then there's this thought
in the next four or five

01:16:19.250 --> 01:16:24.790
years of going to the moon again
and doing the south pole of it,

01:16:24.790 --> 01:16:28.940
and in a way bring in
the private sector,

01:16:28.940 --> 01:16:31.760
some of these space groups
that might get contracted out.

01:16:31.760 --> 01:16:33.740
That to me is more
promising, as long

01:16:33.740 --> 01:16:36.590
as it's done in
the name of peace.

01:16:36.590 --> 01:16:40.520
What we don't want to be
doing is militarizing space.

01:16:40.520 --> 01:16:44.780
And while I'm opposed
to the Space Force

01:16:44.780 --> 01:16:46.520
just personally,
not as a historian,

01:16:46.520 --> 01:16:49.400
as a human looking
at this, I'm more

01:16:49.400 --> 01:16:53.540
inclined to see how we could go
back to the moon in a way that

01:16:53.540 --> 01:16:54.890
would have a positive effect.

01:16:54.890 --> 01:16:58.710
Maybe even a joint visit to
the moon with other countries.

01:16:58.710 --> 01:17:01.220
But I think that might
be a more fertile ground

01:17:01.220 --> 01:17:04.440
for us to explore, and
we do need a treaty.

01:17:04.440 --> 01:17:06.392
FREDERIK LOGEVALL: Yes.

01:17:06.392 --> 01:17:07.350
AUDIENCE: Good evening.

01:17:07.350 --> 01:17:09.150
I'm a researcher from
Boston University,

01:17:09.150 --> 01:17:11.370
and I'm writing a
paper, and I wanted

01:17:11.370 --> 01:17:14.970
to answer the question if,
aside from the competition

01:17:14.970 --> 01:17:16.680
and trying to beat
the Soviets, if there

01:17:16.680 --> 01:17:21.360
was a moral compass guiding
America's actions in the Apollo

01:17:21.360 --> 01:17:22.700
space program?

01:17:22.700 --> 01:17:24.075
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY:
Great question.

01:17:27.150 --> 01:17:30.230
Yeah, only to the degree,
first off, that Kennedy--

01:17:30.230 --> 01:17:31.710
I'll just pick him--

01:17:31.710 --> 01:17:36.180
he truly did not want
to militarize space,

01:17:36.180 --> 01:17:39.173
even though it is
about militarization.

01:17:39.173 --> 01:17:40.590
In many ways, going
to the moon is

01:17:40.590 --> 01:17:43.000
a fig leaf for
rocket development

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:47.970
and weapons of destruction,
but most of the astronauts, not

01:17:47.970 --> 01:17:51.675
Neil Armstrong who stayed very
engineer-focused, but many,

01:17:51.675 --> 01:17:54.450
I'd maybe not say
most, but maybe most,

01:17:54.450 --> 01:17:56.760
came back not thinking
about the moon.

01:17:56.760 --> 01:17:58.260
They thought that
was their mission,

01:17:58.260 --> 01:18:02.610
but seeing Earth, that
blue-green marble floating out

01:18:02.610 --> 01:18:05.820
there, how there are no borders.

01:18:05.820 --> 01:18:10.560
Bill Anders, the astronaut's
famous Earth Rise photograph

01:18:10.560 --> 01:18:13.590
that helped trigger the
environmental movement.

01:18:13.590 --> 01:18:15.600
And when we talk
about NASA today,

01:18:15.600 --> 01:18:17.430
the leading people
on climate change

01:18:17.430 --> 01:18:20.630
have come out of NASA, like
James Hansen and others.

01:18:20.630 --> 01:18:25.050
NASA is doing weather
forecasting, and I mean,

01:18:25.050 --> 01:18:28.220
it's not just we're
shooting rockets up.

01:18:28.220 --> 01:18:31.980
NASA's a very interesting
government agency

01:18:31.980 --> 01:18:35.500
that needs funding.

01:18:35.500 --> 01:18:37.950
And yes, I think
whether it's Whole Earth

01:18:37.950 --> 01:18:41.520
Catalog or the birth of the
Environmental Protection Agency

01:18:41.520 --> 01:18:44.580
and all, it came
out of a moral idea

01:18:44.580 --> 01:18:48.180
that we need to
protect our planet

01:18:48.180 --> 01:18:52.770
and how vulnerable we are and
how lonely it is out there.

01:18:52.770 --> 01:18:55.680
Meaning, we went to the
moon, and it's lifeless.

01:18:55.680 --> 01:18:57.810
Incidentally, we still
don't know really

01:18:57.810 --> 01:18:59.250
how the moon was created.

01:18:59.250 --> 01:19:01.550
Some people think
two planets clashed,

01:19:01.550 --> 01:19:06.930
and a planet hit into Earth,
and it created this moon.

01:19:06.930 --> 01:19:09.540
But what we did find out from
all that moon rock and moon

01:19:09.540 --> 01:19:11.850
soil of the various
Apollo missions

01:19:11.850 --> 01:19:19.010
was the composition of
minerals and the like,

01:19:19.010 --> 01:19:21.763
the deposits we got, were
very much like Earth.

01:19:21.763 --> 01:19:24.180
We thought it would be a little
more different than Earth,

01:19:24.180 --> 01:19:25.847
but there was nothing
that we discovered

01:19:25.847 --> 01:19:27.930
that wasn't
Earth-like, meaning it

01:19:27.930 --> 01:19:30.900
is like a direct
connector to our planet.

01:19:30.900 --> 01:19:33.660
And remember guys, since
the beginning of time,

01:19:33.660 --> 01:19:36.150
the moon sets the ocean tides.

01:19:36.150 --> 01:19:38.370
It's why we have our calendars.

01:19:38.370 --> 01:19:39.930
It's everything.

01:19:39.930 --> 01:19:43.720
And the thought of all these
brilliant Aristotles, Platos,

01:19:43.720 --> 01:19:45.970
Shakespeares staring at the
moon and writing about it,

01:19:45.970 --> 01:19:50.430
and now we were actually
there, is a pretty big thing

01:19:50.430 --> 01:19:52.400
in world history
that we're going

01:19:52.400 --> 01:19:53.650
to be celebrating this summer.

01:19:53.650 --> 01:19:55.108
FREDERIK LOGEVALL:
I'm still trying

01:19:55.108 --> 01:19:58.090
to get my mind around you asking
Neil Armstrong that question

01:19:58.090 --> 01:20:00.780
and him saying "no."

01:20:00.780 --> 01:20:02.790
How can you look at that?

01:20:02.790 --> 01:20:06.480
So yes, and let me say it since
we're running close to the end,

01:20:06.480 --> 01:20:07.882
just remember to be concise.

01:20:07.882 --> 01:20:09.090
We'll move over to this side.

01:20:09.090 --> 01:20:09.450
Thank you.

01:20:09.450 --> 01:20:12.075
AUDIENCE: OK, this is a question
I'm glad I have the two of you

01:20:12.075 --> 01:20:17.310
both for this one, because it's
about Kennedy's speech in 1961.

01:20:17.310 --> 01:20:20.460
And that one is when
he says "go to the moon

01:20:20.460 --> 01:20:22.650
and do the other things."

01:20:22.650 --> 01:20:26.970
And I've always wondered what
the other things could be.

01:20:26.970 --> 01:20:29.820
And you guys are the best
people to ask that of right

01:20:29.820 --> 01:20:30.720
now, probably.

01:20:30.720 --> 01:20:32.970
So do you find out
anything about what

01:20:32.970 --> 01:20:34.110
the other things could be?

01:20:34.110 --> 01:20:35.777
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY:
Well one of the things

01:20:35.777 --> 01:20:39.150
that I write about in the book
is, this isn't just the moon,

01:20:39.150 --> 01:20:41.070
although you heard that
argument with Webb.

01:20:41.070 --> 01:20:42.840
Kennedy is saying
lunar is number one,

01:20:42.840 --> 01:20:47.460
but we were doing probes
of Venus, for example.

01:20:47.460 --> 01:20:49.380
We were doing Mars probes.

01:20:49.380 --> 01:20:51.360
I mean, the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory

01:20:51.360 --> 01:20:56.250
out in Caltech in Pasadena has
been pioneering in the Mars

01:20:56.250 --> 01:20:57.970
rovers and the like.

01:20:57.970 --> 01:21:02.250
And so the idea was to study
all of the solar system

01:21:02.250 --> 01:21:04.920
with our new
technology, not just

01:21:04.920 --> 01:21:06.660
the moon but all of the others.

01:21:06.660 --> 01:21:09.080
That's how I would
interpret that.

01:21:09.080 --> 01:21:12.330
And I write about Mariner
and all of these other--

01:21:12.330 --> 01:21:15.340
you said something
that's very important.

01:21:15.340 --> 01:21:17.730
John F Kennedy really
believed in science,

01:21:17.730 --> 01:21:20.400
believed in scientists,
believed in space exploration,

01:21:20.400 --> 01:21:22.140
because it enhanced science.

01:21:22.140 --> 01:21:26.270
Public discovery is
what Kennedy was about.

01:21:26.270 --> 01:21:29.490
And he was interested
in the ocean also.

01:21:29.490 --> 01:21:33.270
He wanted to deal with
desalinization of ocean water

01:21:33.270 --> 01:21:36.360
to create fresh water for an
arid world and all of this.

01:21:36.360 --> 01:21:38.850
It never caught on
like the moonshot,

01:21:38.850 --> 01:21:42.960
but he had other pet
projects like this.

01:21:42.960 --> 01:21:46.830
To have created a freshwater
system out of ocean water,

01:21:46.830 --> 01:21:49.140
like Kennedy was
constantly talking about

01:21:49.140 --> 01:21:51.360
would have been a
great initiative.

01:21:51.360 --> 01:21:53.310
We're doing it a little
bit in California now,

01:21:53.310 --> 01:21:56.850
but it's so expensive
without federal largesse

01:21:56.850 --> 01:22:00.510
to help that technology along.

01:22:00.510 --> 01:22:02.580
AUDIENCE: Whenever you
talk about or think

01:22:02.580 --> 01:22:05.430
about President
Kennedy's legacy,

01:22:05.430 --> 01:22:08.490
one of the names that always
at least pops up into my mind

01:22:08.490 --> 01:22:10.740
is someone you wrote
a definitive biography

01:22:10.740 --> 01:22:12.840
about, Walter Cronkite.

01:22:12.840 --> 01:22:16.590
And I was wondering if you
could comment upon the coverage

01:22:16.590 --> 01:22:21.930
that Cronkite gave that evening,
when Armstrong stepped foot

01:22:21.930 --> 01:22:22.560
on the moon.

01:22:22.560 --> 01:22:23.220
Thank you.

01:22:23.220 --> 01:22:23.520
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY: Great.

01:22:23.520 --> 01:22:25.140
I have a photo of Cronkite.

01:22:25.140 --> 01:22:29.820
And Cronkite was considered the
eighth astronaut of the Mercury

01:22:29.820 --> 01:22:30.780
7.

01:22:30.780 --> 01:22:36.060
He was a bonanza of PR for NASA,
because Cronkite in World War

01:22:36.060 --> 01:22:38.290
II was the dean of Air Force.

01:22:38.290 --> 01:22:42.780
He was embedded with the
UP, UPI it used to be.

01:22:42.780 --> 01:22:44.850
Some people called it
the old United Press

01:22:44.850 --> 01:22:48.240
Services, wire services.

01:22:48.240 --> 01:22:51.780
Learned all of the Air
Force pilots, et cetera.

01:22:51.780 --> 01:22:54.300
So aviation, when he
came back after World War

01:22:54.300 --> 01:23:01.435
II in the Korean War period, he
took on a beat nobody wanted--

01:23:01.435 --> 01:23:01.935
space.

01:23:04.530 --> 01:23:08.100
And he was grew up in Houston,
Texas, Walter Cronkite.

01:23:08.100 --> 01:23:11.430
And so he got to know
a lot of the early NASA

01:23:11.430 --> 01:23:14.430
people by the late '50s, but
also pilots from World War II,

01:23:14.430 --> 01:23:16.020
and Air Force
people, and all this,

01:23:16.020 --> 01:23:17.940
and he had a great Rolodex.

01:23:17.940 --> 01:23:22.710
And he is a fanatic
about space, Cronkite.

01:23:22.710 --> 01:23:25.080
And like John F Kennedy,
he loved sailing.

01:23:25.080 --> 01:23:27.180
You'd be amazed at how
many people like sailing

01:23:27.180 --> 01:23:30.480
in the ocean that have
become space buffs.

01:23:30.480 --> 01:23:32.590
It's remarkable how many.

01:23:32.590 --> 01:23:35.330
But without Cronkite,
that night of Cronkite,

01:23:35.330 --> 01:23:37.290
it was just classic coverage.

01:23:37.290 --> 01:23:40.260
I wrote in my book, out of
all the things Cronkite did,

01:23:40.260 --> 01:23:43.980
his hours and hours of
coverage of Apollo 11

01:23:43.980 --> 01:23:46.680
was the maestro
moment of his career,

01:23:46.680 --> 01:23:49.020
because he had so well
educated himself and had

01:23:49.020 --> 01:23:52.185
so many contacts, and they
re-created things at CBS.

01:23:52.185 --> 01:23:55.050
It was really a
marvel of television.

01:23:55.050 --> 01:23:56.460
FREDERIK LOGEVALL:
Let's do this.

01:23:56.460 --> 01:23:59.250
This may be a mistake, and I
