01:25:27.995 --> 01:25:29.870
And I wondered if you
could say a little more

01:25:29.870 --> 01:25:32.300
about the impact of that
on both the schedule

01:25:32.300 --> 01:25:35.010
and the motivation.

01:25:35.010 --> 01:25:36.360
FREDERIK LOGEVALL: Finally, yes.

01:25:36.360 --> 01:25:38.670
AUDIENCE: My question is
an earth shot question,

01:25:38.670 --> 01:25:39.690
so to speak.

01:25:39.690 --> 01:25:44.760
Is there any-- do you see any
opportunity for NOAA to become

01:25:44.760 --> 01:25:47.100
as big a--

01:25:47.100 --> 01:25:51.882
National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Association--

01:25:51.882 --> 01:25:57.920
to be sort of the leader in
a new American inspiration

01:25:57.920 --> 01:26:03.200
and a new political practicality
of distributing resources

01:26:03.200 --> 01:26:05.547
to areas that need
to be developed?

01:26:05.547 --> 01:26:07.130
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY:
OK, great questions.

01:26:07.130 --> 01:26:09.530
I like the idea of never
letting somebody stand

01:26:09.530 --> 01:26:12.970
at the mic at the end, so we got
everybody in the conversation.

01:26:12.970 --> 01:26:17.900
With the China question, China
is doing a great job right now

01:26:17.900 --> 01:26:19.100
in space exploration.

01:26:19.100 --> 01:26:23.060
They're putting a lot
of their energy into it.

01:26:23.060 --> 01:26:26.100
And they are exploring
the dark side of the moon.

01:26:26.100 --> 01:26:28.090
And if we do a
national thing, it

01:26:28.090 --> 01:26:31.070
may be a space race
with China, let's hope

01:26:31.070 --> 01:26:34.370
it can be done in a way that's
not militarized but in a way

01:26:34.370 --> 01:26:37.370
that it's a friendly
competition.

01:26:37.370 --> 01:26:42.220
Mars is still out there
on everybody's mind.

01:26:42.220 --> 01:26:44.660
NOAA, amazing operation.

01:26:44.660 --> 01:26:48.920
In fact, former head of NOAA
was the first woman, Kathryn

01:26:48.920 --> 01:26:52.310
Sullivan, she was
recently head of NOAA,

01:26:52.310 --> 01:26:55.000
and she was the first
woman spacewalker.

01:26:55.000 --> 01:26:56.970
There's a great
connection to NOAA.

01:26:56.970 --> 01:27:00.200
I would think the
oceans is a moonshot,

01:27:00.200 --> 01:27:02.120
cleaning of the
world's oceans is one

01:27:02.120 --> 01:27:05.620
that I would think everybody
would want to get behind.

01:27:05.620 --> 01:27:06.890
[APPLAUSE]

01:27:06.890 --> 01:27:10.910
And NOAA could take a great lead
in the United States on that.

01:27:10.910 --> 01:27:13.010
That's an amazing--
it's funny, you

01:27:13.010 --> 01:27:18.710
say NOAA and NASA are both
remarkable government agencies.

01:27:18.710 --> 01:27:22.640
And Gus Grissom
and Chaffee, White,

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:26.140
that was a shocking
event when they all died

01:27:26.140 --> 01:27:28.010
and whether Apollo
could be canceled.

01:27:28.010 --> 01:27:31.850
It led, in fact, to Webb
by '68 got muscled out

01:27:31.850 --> 01:27:33.890
by Lyndon to head NASA.

01:27:33.890 --> 01:27:35.570
Some people blamed him.

01:27:35.570 --> 01:27:37.790
It was inevitable that
it was going to happen.

01:27:37.790 --> 01:27:40.400
They always thought the
deaths would occur in space,

01:27:40.400 --> 01:27:42.290
but here it was on the ground.

01:27:42.290 --> 01:27:44.780
But it didn't defund
or derail Apollo,

01:27:44.780 --> 01:27:50.030
but really, for people like Neil
Armstrong, it's not hyperbole.

01:27:50.030 --> 01:27:55.670
He figured he had a 50-50
chance of surviving Apollo 11.

01:27:55.670 --> 01:27:58.440
That's how brave these
Apollo astronauts were.

01:27:58.440 --> 01:28:03.680
Imagine your family right after,
oh, Apollo 1, all of them die.

01:28:03.680 --> 01:28:08.870
And now you're having
your loved one go up,

01:28:08.870 --> 01:28:11.120
the wives of those astronauts.

01:28:11.120 --> 01:28:12.440
Did I miss one of them?

01:28:12.440 --> 01:28:13.010
One last one?

01:28:13.010 --> 01:28:15.980
FREDERIK LOGEVALL: No, I think
you got them all, including

01:28:15.980 --> 01:28:16.940
the earth shot.

01:28:16.940 --> 01:28:19.270
You get a sense,
ladies and gentlemen,

01:28:19.270 --> 01:28:23.240
of why Doug Brinkley
is celebrated,

01:28:23.240 --> 01:28:25.820
why you need to read this book.

01:28:25.820 --> 01:28:28.240
I want to thank all of you
for coming this evening,

01:28:28.240 --> 01:28:32.060
and please join me in thanking
Doug Brinkley for this.

01:28:32.060 --> 01:28:33.560
[APPLAUSE]

01:28:34.160 --> 01:28:36.260
DOUGLAS BRINKLEY: Yes.

